		<p>I am Native American with parents from two different tribes, and I was adopted by my biological mothers family.  I grew up knowing who my birth parents were and I knew that they were from two different tribes.  I found out years ago that my biological father&#8217;s family hated my mother.  I was invited to spend a weekend with my bio-fathers mother and I chose to go to my bio-mother&#8217;s wedding that same weekend.  My bio-grandma won&#8217;t take my calls or respond back too me, as well as any family member from my fathers side. Recently I have been scratched on my legs and upper body. I have had 3 miscarriages and recently I was choked until I almost passed out.  Everytime my mom tries to smudge me the sage won&#8217;t stay lit.  My mom believes that I have had a &#8220;Bearwalk&#8221; put on me, which in my tribe is a curse from someone who wants to do great bodily harm on you.  I am just looking for advice on what I should do. Please.</p>

		<div class="reply">
				</div>
				</div>
		</li>
		<li class="comment byuser comment-author-admin bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-7187">
				<div id="div-comment-7187" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<cite class="fn">Veleda</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.sourcememory.net/veleda/?p=63#comment-7187">
			August 21, 2012 at 10:21 pm</a>		</div>

		<p>First, don&#8217;t get caught in fear, which makes you more vulnerable. You don&#8217;t say what the traditions are but i wouldn&#8217;t be able to advise you for those anyway. However, you are a child of Earth and can always turn to Nature for protection. Chant any prayer, any song that brings you close to the Sacred, calling and asking for help. Do it at least twice a day, it isn&#8217;t about form, having some right words, but about the heartfelt call. Walk on the land. Offer a little tobacco to places where you feel the power is strong. Keep asking for help and guidance and protection. See yourself bathed in light, and all ill energies turned away from you, falling away and sinking into the earth. Wash yourself with salt water with the intention of clearing away the hateful energy, or with water perfumed with lavender or other essential oil. Sage is excellent for transforming negative forces; if it won&#8217;t stay lit, persevere. You can either get the little charcoals for burning myrrh or you can make your own fire and use those coals. Don&#8217;t be intimidated, your spiritual will and persistence will win out, can prevail, will prevail. It doesn&#8217;t have to be sage, it could be mugwort which is the same family, or cedar or sweetgrass. Ask for help from your ancestors, or any Beings you hold sacred, ask for guidance in your dreams. Even better if you can find someone who holds sweatlodges, who knows what they&#8217;re doing, and not connected with the hateful family. Take little patches of cloth, place tobacco into them and tie them up with prayers. Put them around your doorway, over or beside your bed. You can also take a cord, a new cord, yarn or string, smudge it, and tie knots in it to bind all energies intended to harm you. Put your prayers into the cord, and then place it somewhere, on your home altar, or in a tree hollow near your house, or in the ground outside your door. These are acts of intention that increase your spiritual protection. You have the power within you to turn this away, to send the energy back. You don&#8217;t have to take it. Just have faith in whatever you hold most Sacred, Don&#8217;t be afraid to ask for help from that Source. Play spiritual music in your home. Avoid people who might harm you, seek out positive allies. Ask for good people to come into your life. Most of all, calm yourself, don&#8217;t panic, and take positive action with full faith.</p>

		<div class="reply">
				</div>
				</div>
		</li>
		<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-8084">
				<div id="div-comment-8084" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=100003406771970' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Akira</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.sourcememory.net/veleda/?p=63#comment-8084">
			October 7, 2012 at 2:37 pm</a>		</div>

		<p>Dear Kyōshin,Thanks for your response. I&#8217;ve read your commnets several times now, but I don&#8217;t understand what it was about my post that might have caused you to be aware of your  spiritual homelessness.  To me, a home is something we make (are continually making), not something we find. And, right, who can whole-heartedly regret the comforts that industry has given us? I hope you don&#8217;t think I was, in some way, trying to pit a romanticized Native American culture against contemporary industrial culture. The festival was merely a backdrop for an experience that could just as easily have happened in an urban Christian church. However, I do feel that something like a harvest festival (from any culture) which acknowledges the change of seasons speaks more clearly to my personal emotional and mental world of late than a Labor Day holiday.My own Christian upbringing didn&#8217;t leave a bad taste in my mouth. My father is a lapsed Roman Catholic and my mother has been associated with the Methodist church for most of her life, but would probably simply identify herself as a Christian (who also reads books on Judaism and Buddhism). In my late teens and early 20s, when I began to develop a more sophisticated view of the social and political world around me, a period of distaste for Christianity began. Not a distaste for my parents&#8217; version of the religion, but for one that had the power to hold hurtful dogmas over others and refused to permit other ways of thinking and being. In my twenties, I jokingly referred to the  Christian Military Industrial Complex.&#8217; I think there&#8217;s still some truth to this term, in the US, at least. Even before my early adulthood, though, I had a basic sense that the churches I had attended up to that point were trying to contain something much greater than the ministers could even imagine; they were describing life in small words in such a shallow either/or way; there was a real lack of ease with mystery. I did a lot of camping during this time and my appreciation for the vast mystery of the natural world became my first religion of choice. Discovering the writings of Laozi and Zhuangzi in my twenties, and later Buddhism, opened up a religious world that seemed to acknowledge experiences and views that I developed before I had ever heard of such people or ways of thought/being. I have made peace with Christianity, though. My wife, as you know, is a Christian, but one, due to her Chinese Buddhist roots and own spiritual inclinations, has been deeply influenced by modern Dharmic writers and teachers. These days because of where I live, ironically, I spend more time in Christian churches than in Buddhist temples, and I feel quite at home  usually. The  home&#8217; I am constantly creating is surely filled with a lot of post-modern simulacra, but these are the building blocks we have. That&#8217;s one of the things I enjoy so much about Dōgen. He didn&#8217;t buy into the mappō (Age of Decline) narrative of his day or, at least, had a different answer to it in comparison with the other new schools of the Kamakura period. It seems like he figured a human living in 13th century Japan had just as much potential for enlightenment or delusion as one living during the time of Shakyamuni.</p>

		<div class="reply">
				</div>
				</div>
		</li>
			</ol>
			
			
